ferent translations =\r\nby different parties. \nAurobindo even says that it is purely allegorical, h=\r\ne mostly \ninterpreted some selective hymns. Never in any of the hyms does t=\r\nhere exist any \nremote hint of any sort of physical immortality, merely des=\r\ncribing different \nstates of spiritual process internal to the sadhaka. The=\r\n other translations by \nother commentators also do not mention any sort of =\r\nphysical immortality at all.\n \nTherefore, for complete lack of any evidence=\r\n from any quarter I shall have to \nassumed that vedas do not talk of any so=\r\nrt of physical immortality.\n \nRishis wouldn&#39;t put the method for divinizing=\r\n the Physical body in plaintext, to \ndisallow its misuse. It is for the per=\r\nsevering soul to find it out for himself \nor through the upliftment of mass=\r\n consciousness through Vedas.\n\nWhy Vedic Rishis wouldn&#39;t do it themselves, =\r\nor if they did it, nobody would \nknow,\n \nThere is no evidence that the Rish=\r\nis become physically immortal in the body. You \nare *assuming* that Rishis =\r\n*might have* put some hidden hint, but thats just an \nassumption. They may =\r\nvery well have not put any such hint about any physical \nimmortality, speci=\r\nally since none of the Rishis themselves became physically \nimmortal. For a=\r\nn assumption to be reasonable, it must have some \nbasis/hint/example. We fi=\r\nnd no such conclusive examples in the history of \nSanatana Dharma, except a=\r\n few stray cases like Ashwathama. \n\n \nNeither does any of the translation o=\r\nf the Vedas by different people speak of \nany such state achievable. Techni=\r\ncally someone who is physically immortal is one \nwho stays in the body till=\r\n end of the cycle of creation. Even Babaji - who is \nsupposedly physically =\r\nimmortal - does say that others cannot remain till the end \nof creation. So=\r\n the evidence, rather overwhelmingly, is against the existence or \neven pos=\r\nsiblity of such a state.\n \n&gt; Because if one is immortal in the physical bod=\r\ny, one must survive in it till \n&gt;the end of creation.\nOTOH, a soul liberate=\r\nd in Physical body, is no longer bound by the rules of \ncreation as applica=\r\nble to mortal beings, who have to die despite all the jnana \nthey attain.\n =\r\n\nBut strangely that is a state no one has achieved. Neither the seers of th=\r\ne \nVedas achieve it - there is no evidence anywhere that they did - nor did=\r\n \nthey recommend it to others. \n\n \nEven Babaji says only he will exist till=\r\n the end. And if your assumptions are \ncorrect, then Babaji has to be wrong=\r\n!\n \nI guess I just have to reject this notion for complete lack of any evid=\r\nence of \nthe same, and peacefully, agree to disagree with you.\n \n-Regards\n =\r\nRajarshi\n\n \n&quot;Between me and You, there is only me. \nTake away the me, so on=\r\nly You remain&quot; - Hallaj\n\n\n\n\n________________________________\n From: silenta=\r\ndmirer_in &lt;silentadmirer_in@...&gt;\nTo: vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com\nSen=\r\nt: Mon, 29 November, 2010 7:13:23 PM\nSubject: [vedic-wisdom] On Shakti (Re:=\r\n Success with Mantras)\n\n  \nNamaskar,\nThe aim of my mails is only to free th=\r\ne minds of the reader from biases, caused \nby dominating propaganda of Veda=\r\nntists - that is to see the Physical body as \nsomething to be ignored for s=\r\npiritual pursuit. Consequently, Vedantists \nthemselves never found out the =\r\ntruth about the Physical body consciousness as an \nexpression of divine con=\r\nsciousness. The Bhagavad Gita, is a text, not from a \nVedic Rishi, but a Ve=\r\ndantist Vishnu Avatara.\nThere is a need to bring the Vedas to the mass cons=\r\nciousness, to uplift the \nPhysical consciousness from where it is now.\n\nRis=\r\nhis wouldn&#39;t put the method for divinizing the Physical body in plaintext, =\r\nto \ndisallow its misuse. It is for the persevering soul to find it out for =\r\nhimself \nor through the upli